IDE.\r\n\r\nLooks some of the recent changes in UI/SWT area caused that, bugzilla never saw that error before.\r\nFirst one was reported with  4.24.0.I20220504-0230 build, but that doesn't mean this {"id":1226472743,"created_at":"2022-05-05T10:12:03Z","updated_at":"2022-05-18T08:41:30Z","state":"closed","title":"FileDialog does not remember previous directory","html_url":"https://github.com/eclipse-platform/eclipse.platform.swt/issues/95","body":"Windows 10\r\nEclipse 4.23 and 4.24\r\n\r\nThis seems to be a regression as this is working in Eclipse 4.22 but not in 4.23 and 4.24.\r\n\r\nIn the SWT as used in Eclipse 4.22 and earlier, a FileDialog would remember the last open directory. In the SWT in Eclipse 4.23 and later it reverts to the root \"Computer\" directory on Windows.\r\n\r\nRun the snippet below against a target of Eclipse 4.22 and compare with a target of 4.23. Click the \"Open\" button, navigate to a file and open this. Repeat. On Eclipse 4.22 target the previous directory is remembered. Not on 4.23 target.\r\n\r\n```java\r\nimport org.eclipse.swt.SWT;\r\nimport org.eclipse.swt.events.SelectionAdapter;\r\nimport org.eclipse.swt.events.SelectionEvent;\r\nimport org.eclipse.swt.layout.GridLayout;\r\nimport org.eclipse.swt.widgets.Button;\r\nimport org.eclipse.swt.widgets.Display;\r\nimport org.eclipse.swt.widgets.FileDialog;\r\nimport org.eclipse.swt.widgets.Shell;\r\n\r\npublic class FileOpen {\r\n\r\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\r\n        Display display = new Display();\r\n        Shell shell = new Shell(display);\r\n        shell.setLayout(new GridLayout());\r\n        shell.setSize(300, 200);\r\n        \r\n        Button button = new Button(shell, SWT.PUSH);\r\n        button.setText(\"Open\");\r\n        button.addSelectionListener(new SelectionAdapter() {\r\n            @Override\r\n            public void widgetSelected(SelectionEvent e) {\r\n                new FileDialog(shell, SWT.OPEN).open();\r\n            }\r\n        });\r\n        \r\n        shell.open();\r\n\r\n        while(!shell.isDisposed()) {\r\n            if(!display.readAndDispatch()) display.sleep();\r\n        }\r\n        display.dispose();\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n"}

{"id":1226922344,"created_at":"2022-05-05T16:32:18Z","updated_at":"2022-05-05T19:45:46Z","state":"closed","title":"LockManager.handleException errors on shutdown (#56)","html_url":"https://github.com/eclipse-platform/eclipse.platform.ui/pull/59","body":"1) Fixed unneeded calls to display from aboutToRelease(). All what we\r\nwant is to \"null\" \"ui\" field if we are in UI thread. For that we don't\r\nneed to check isUI() and Display because \"ui\" reference should be either\r\nUI thread (which can be compared directly with current thread) or it is\r\nnull and we don't care.\r\n\r\n2) Fixed race condition in isUI(), which assumes the display is not\r\ndisposed after the display.isDisposed() check. But since we are not\r\nguaranteed to be in UI thread, someone could have disposed Display in\r\nthe meantime. So just call Thread.currentThread() that already does this\r\ncheck for us.\r\n\r\nSee https://github.com/eclipse-platform/eclipse.platform.ui/issues/56"}

{"id":1246044049,"created_at":"2022-05-24T06:22:32Z","updated_at":"2022-05-25T05:49:36Z","state":"closed","title":"BorderLayout do not work well together with RowLayout","html_url":"https://github.com/eclipse-platform/eclipse.platform.swt/issues/163","body":"Because `BorderLayout` currently do not constrain the size of a component a priory  using a `RowLayout` in the TOP area will cut components that are normally wrapped (the same problem occurs with any wrapping component).\r\n\r\nOne can see the behavior by slightly modify [Snippet379](https://github.com/eclipse-platform/eclipse.platform.swt/blob/master/examples/org.eclipse.swt.snippets/src/org/eclipse/swt/snippets/Snippet379.java):\r\n\r\n```\r\nComposite composite = region(new Composite(shell, 0), SWT.TOP);\r\ncomposite.setLayout(new RowLayout());\r\nfor (int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {\r\n\tLabel label = new Label(composite, SWT.NONE);\r\n\tlabel.setText(\"Label \"+(i+1));\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nthis will result in the following:\r\n\r\n![grafik](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1331477/169961493-4b74260e-9295-4e11-8677-aca9584292a9.png)\r\n\r\nIf one now make the window smaller, the labels are cut of from the right:\r\n\r\n![grafik](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1331477/169961630-9a7e0496-da86-407a-bf33-c41d64b6db89.png)\r\n\r\nThis is because `RowLayout` (if unconstrained) do not need to wrap and always returns the height for a single line. If we then set the final size of the component, the wrapped items are hidden because the height is now fixed.\r\n\r\nJust for completeness, `GridLayout` suffer from the same problem here:\r\n\r\n![grafik](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1331477/169962473-1f9b0a67-f74f-415f-afa0-d70cfa9f29e2.png)\r\n\r\nAlso see this related Discussion:\r\n- https://github.com/eclipse-platform/eclipse.platform.swt/discussions/161"}

{"id":1226472743,"created_at":"2022-05-05T10:12:03Z","updated_at":"2022-05-18T08:41:30Z","state":"closed","title":"FileDialog does not remember previous directory","html_url":"https://github.com/eclipse-platform/eclipse.platform.swt/issues/95","body":"Windows 10\r\nEclipse 4.23 and 4.24\r\n\r\nThis seems to be a regression as this is working in Eclipse 4.22 but not in 4.23 and 4.24.\r\n\r\nIn the SWT as used in Eclipse 4.22 and earlier, a FileDialog would remember the last open directory. In the SWT in Eclipse 4.23 and later it reverts to the root \"Computer\" directory on Windows.\r\n\r\nRun the snippet below against a target of Eclipse 4.22 and compare with a target of 4.23. Click the \"Open\" button, navigate to a file and open this. Repeat. On Eclipse 4.22 target the previous directory is remembered. Not on 4.23 target.\r\n\r\n```java\r\nimport org.eclipse.swt.SWT;\r\nimport org.eclipse.swt.events.SelectionAdapter;\r\nimport org.eclipse.swt.events.SelectionEvent;\r\nimport org.eclipse.swt.layout.GridLayout;\r\nimport org.eclipse.swt.widgets.Button;\r\nimport org.eclipse.swt.widgets.Display;\r\nimport org.eclipse.swt.widgets.FileDialog;\r\nimport org.eclipse.swt.widgets.Shell;\r\n\r\npublic class FileOpen {\r\n\r\n    public static void main(String[] args) {\r\n        Display display = new Display();\r\n        Shell shell = new Shell(display);\r\n        shell.setLayout(new GridLayout());\r\n        shell.setSize(300, 200);\r\n        \r\n        Button button = new Button(shell, SWT.PUSH);\r\n        button.setText(\"Open\");\r\n        button.addSelectionListener(new SelectionAdapter() {\r\n            @Override\r\n            public void widgetSelected(SelectionEvent e) {\r\n                new FileDialog(shell, SWT.OPEN).open();\r\n            }\r\n        });\r\n        \r\n        shell.open();\r\n\r\n        while(!shell.isDisposed()) {\r\n            if(!display.readAndDispatch()) display.sleep();\r\n        }\r\n        display.dispose();\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n"}

{"id":1226922344,"created_at":"2022-05-05T16:32:18Z","updated_at":"2022-05-05T19:45:46Z","state":"closed","title":"LockManager.handleException errors on shutdown (#56)","html_url":"https://github.com/eclipse-platform/eclipse.platform.ui/pull/59","body":"1) Fixed unneeded calls to display from aboutToRelease(). All what we\r\nwant is to \"null\" \"ui\" field if we are in UI thread. For that we don't\r\nneed to check isUI() and Display because \"ui\" reference should be either\r\nUI thread (which can be compared directly with current thread) or it is\r\nnull and we don't care.\r\n\r\n2) Fixed race condition in isUI(), which assumes the display is not\r\ndisposed after the display.isDisposed() check. But since we are not\r\nguaranteed to be in UI thread, someone could have disposed Display in\r\nthe meantime. So just call Thread.currentThread() that already does this\r\ncheck for us.\r\n\r\nSee https://github.com/eclipse-platform/eclipse.platform.ui/issues/56"}

{"id":1246044049,"created_at":"2022-05-24T06:22:32Z","updated_at":"2022-05-25T05:49:36Z","state":"closed","title":"BorderLayout do not work well together with RowLayout","html_url":"https://github.com/eclipse-platform/eclipse.platform.swt/issues/163","body":"Because `BorderLayout` currently do not constrain the size of a component a priory  using a `RowLayout` in the TOP area will cut components that are normally wrapped (the same problem occurs with any wrapping component).\r\n\r\nOne can see the behavior by slightly modify [Snippet379](https://github.com/eclipse-platform/eclipse.platform.swt/blob/master/examples/org.eclipse.swt.snippets/src/org/eclipse/swt/snippets/Snippet379.java):\r\n\r\n```\r\nComposite composite = region(new Composite(shell, 0), SWT.TOP);\r\ncomposite.setLayout(new RowLayout());\r\nfor (int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {\r\n\tLabel label = new Label(composite, SWT.NONE);\r\n\tlabel.setText(\"Label \"+(i+1));\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nthis will result in the following:\r\n\r\n![grafik](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1331477/169961493-4b74260e-9295-4e11-8677-aca9584292a9.png)\r\n\r\nIf one now make the window smaller, the labels are cut of from the right:\r\n\r\n![grafik](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1331477/169961630-9a7e0496-da86-407a-bf33-c41d64b6db89.png)\r\n\r\nThis is because `RowLayout` (if unconstrained) do not need to wrap and always returns the height for a single line. If we then set the final size of the component, the wrapped items are hidden because the height is now fixed.\r\n\r\nJust for completeness, `GridLayout` suffer from the same problem here:\r\n\r\n![grafik](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1331477/169962473-1f9b0a67-f74f-415f-afa0-d70cfa9f29e2.png)\r\n\r\nAlso see this related Discussion:\r\n- https://github.com/eclipse-platform/eclipse.platform.swt/discussions/161"}

{"id":1215554938,"created_at":"2022-04-26T07:53:43Z","updated_at":"2022-05-09T09:26:03Z","state":"closed","title":"IEP-687 Random NPE when opening the launch configuration options","html_url":"https://github.com/espressif/idf-eclipse-plugin/pull/526","body":"Briefly about the issue. Sometimes launch configurations are bugged for some reason, so it's impossible to edit them because of the NPE in process of getting the build configuration. As figured out, the problem is similar to the old problem with \"Build not configured correctly\", which we fixed a long time ago. \r\n\r\nThe fix for that issue is to recheck configs and put any of the ESP toolchains to the settings, so it will be possible to create an IDF build configuration. Since we already have code for these purposes, this PR is mainly about refactoring and using the same code in different places."}

{"id":1236188928,"created_at":"2022-05-15T05:04:45Z","updated_at":"2022-05-25T02:47:38Z","state":"closed","title":"Several problems with synchronised views and the new OpenGL architecture","html_url":"https://github.com/gama-platform/gama/issues/3421","body":"**Describe the bug**\r\nThe new OpenGL architecture, that relies on NEWT Windows (defined in JOGL), requires that the update of displays take place in the main thread (i.e. the SWT thread) and be synchronous. This creates several issues in the presence of displays synchronised with the simulation: blocking of threads, blocking of the simulation when one of the displays is not updating because it is not visible to SWT, etc. (see for instance #3414 and probably #3406). \r\n\r\n_Reminder_:  the new OpenGL architecture is mandatory as it is the only one working for 1.8.2 on macOS and Linux (see #3199 and related issues). \r\n\r\n**This is a blocking issue for the release of 1.8.2**.\r\n\r\n**Proposal**\r\nSolving this issue requires a (welcome) change in the semantics of `synchronized:` and some digging into the inter threading behaviours of the displays/outputs/outputmanagers of GAMA. \r\n\r\n1. Removal (deprecation) of `synchronized:` at the level of displays or other outputs\r\n2. Addition of `synchronized:` at the level of `output` and `permanent` : now all displays are synchronised together (or not). This solves the semantic problem of what it meant for only one display to be synchronised among unsynchronised outputs.\r\n3. Removal of the corresponding buttons in the interface and addition of a global 'sync' button in the experiment controls, next to the `delay slider` \r\n\r\nAny comments appreciated !\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n**Desktop (please complete the following information):**\r\n - OS: all\r\n - GAMA version: 1.8.2 git\r\n"}

{"id":1225409806,"created_at":"2022-05-04T13:56:19Z","updated_at":"2022-05-04T14:10:30Z","state":"closed","title":"Support Content Security Policy (a.k.a CSP) to help protect against XSS","html_url":"https://github.com/eclipse-rap/org.eclipse.rap/issues/12","body":"**Copy of Bugzilla [bug 579074](https://bugs.eclipse.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=579074)**\r\n\r\nIf using a CSP header with RAP it would need to be configured with a CSP `script-src` directive with `self`, `unsafe-inline`, `unsafe-eval`.\r\n\r\nSuch a configurtion is very permissive and removes most of the security provided by CSP.\r\n\r\n[csp-evaluator.withgoogle.com](https://csp-evaluator.withgoogle.com/) allows to evaluate how a CSP configuration improves XSS protection and currently rates `scripts-src` values as follows:\r\n- `unsafe-inline` as **High severity**:\r\n  `unsafe-inline` allows the execution of unsafe in-page scripts and event handlers.\r\n- `self` as **Possible medium** severity finding:\r\n  `self` can be problematic if you host JSONP, Angular or user uploaded files.\r\n- `unsafe-eval` as **Possible medium** severity finding:\r\n  `unsafe-eval` allows the execution of code injected into DOM APIs such as `eval()`.\r\n\r\n\r\nIdeally the script-src tag should not be configured with any of `unsafe-inline`, `self`, or `unsafe-eval`. \r\n- `unsafe-inline` is required because `org.eclipse.rap.rwt.internal.service.StartupPage` generates a script element with inline code. \r\n- `self` is required because `org.eclipse.rap.rwt.internal.service.StartupPage` generates a script element with a src from server.\r\n- `unsafe-eval` is required because RAP uses the `eval()` function for several features (Browser widget, client scripting and JavaScriptExecutor, BrowserFunction).\r\n\r\nThe proposed enhancement is to support configuring `RWTServlet` to generate a \"strict\" CSP header:\r\n\r\nWhen CSP generation is enabled RWTServlet.sendStartupContent would:\r\n- generate a nonce on request\r\n- add a CSP header to the response: `Content-Security-Policy: default-src 'self'; script-src nonce-<generatedvalue> 'unsafe-eval'; style-src 'self' 'unsafe-inline'`\r\n- pass the generated nonce to the `StartupPage` so that it can append the nonce to the `<script>` elements.\r\n\r\n\r\nAdditionally:\r\n- `RWTServlet` could be configured to remove `unsafe-eval` from the `src-script`. \r\n  In such a situation RAP features relying on JavaScript `eval()` would become unusable.\r\n- `RWTServlet` could be configured to add other CSP directives like frame-ancestors"}

{"id":1215620761,"created_at":"2022-04-26T08:49:44Z","updated_at":"2022-05-05T10:29:43Z","state":"closed","title":"Combine declaration and init removing overriding assignment Bug 572440","html_url":"https://github.com/eclipse-jdt/eclipse.jdt.ui/pull/27","body":"# What it does\r\n\r\nCombines the initialization and declaration of variables when cleaning up overriding assignments given two conditions:\r\n\r\n1. The assignment expression is not used\r\n2. The initialization expression either is passive or the assignment immediately follows the declaration of the variable.\r\n\r\nBoth conditions intend to ensure that behaviour is preserved.\r\n\r\nFixes https://bugs.eclipse.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=572440\r\n\r\n# How to test\r\n* Turn on \"Remove overridden assignment\" on the \"Unnecessary Code\" cleanup configuration page\r\n* Run `Source->Cleanup\" with code like this:\r\n```java\r\n// Keep this comment\r\nboolean reassignedVar = true;\r\nreassignedVar = \"\\\\n\".equals(File.pathSeparator);\r\nreturn reassignedVar;\r\n```"}

generated Java code, an IllegalArgumentException occurs, \"[null]\" is an unhandled parameter type. Indeed, there is no 'if-case' which handles the expression being null. Going up one call, this method is being called from de.cau.cs.kieler.scg.klighd.SCGraphHierarchySynthesis.synthesizeBasicBlocks in this case (line 253 as of 2021-08-24 13:13). Here, the method is called in an if-block with the guard\r\n`schedulingBlock.guards.head !== null`\r\n\r\nHowever, the argument that is actually passed is \"schedulingBlock.guards.head.expression\". Thus, if the 'expression' is null, this is still called, and causes the error we see in the StackTrace.\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nComparing this to an older version, these two methods did not change regarding this specific call. The problem is originating from somewhere else - for some reason, the expression of a guards.head has become null.\r\n\r\nVersion Analysis:\r\n\r\nKieler Release 1.2.0 does not have this issue. The nightly build (2021-08-24) does. A change after 2021-07-05 must thus be the cause. 5 pull requests were merged since then (#268, #263, #271, #270, #272).\r\n\r\nTesting:\r\n\r\n2870ca03e55572cc1af0c02e96c3dd618d2692db - Same error\r\n8fa8c10b781a13aee8c09982d0c418732ab937cc - Same error\r\nfe02074930a7b45565c0a28339688aa5ecde20bb - Same error\r\nbf317f8626b9992173521fade39584c3544c1afe - Same error\r\n1de7a94385bca76c42c21ec70284f760c82186a6 - No error\r\n--> As bf317f86... is the direct successor of 1de7a94..., the changes in that commit must be the reason for the problem.\r\n\r\nAnalysis of bf317f8626b9992173521fade39584c3544c1afe:\r\nThe description says:\r\n\"scg: Improved handling of annotations in SCG.\r\n\r\nAll annotations are now passed on and need to be filtered explicity.\r\nOpposite behavior as before.\"\r\n\r\nMore can be seen here: https://git.rtsys.informatik.uni-kiel.de/projects/KIELER/repos/semantics/commits/bf317f8626b9992173521fade39584c3544c1afe\r\n\r\nOn first sight, I am unable to identify a specific reason why these changes cause the issue. The description says that the filtering behavior is now opposite as before - maybe something in the visualization part was not adjusted to account for this? I am not sure."}

{"id":1193887241,"created_at":"2022-04-06T01:10:02Z","updated_at":"2022-04-06T08:50:34Z","state":"closed","title":"[win32] HDC leak in Image.createGdipImage()","html_url":"https://github.com/eclipse-platform/eclipse.platform.swt/issues/21","body":"[Bug 493455](https://bugs.eclipse.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=493455) accidentally removed `device.internal_dispose_GC(hDC, null)` from `Image.createGdipImage()` on win32, which now leaks one `HDC` per image created. Note that `GC.drawImage()` may create the image internally.\r\n\r\nAs the leak grows, Windows get slower. When leak reaches 10000 (default maximum for one process), SWT will begin to throw `SWT.error()` and UI begins to malfunction.\r\n\r\nI'll provide a patch."}

{"id":1220074181,"created_at":"2022-04-29T07:13:32Z","updated_at":"2022-05-06T16:55:40Z","state":"closed","title":"let readAndDispatch() handle multiple messages","html_url":"https://github.com/eclipse-platform/eclipse.platform.swt/issues/79","body":"During https://github.com/eclipse-platform/eclipse.platform.swt/pull/78 is see a hotspots in readAndDispatch for the costly checks for system messages. We could avoid those if we handle multiple internal messages before polling OS again. \r\nTo avoid unresponsiveness to OS we could limit that internal message handling to a duration of for example 1ms.\r\n\r\nThis improves the BenchmarkSwtMultithreading handling from ~ 190ms to ~ 88ms on my Windows computer.\r\nWDYT?\r\nI know it is against the javadoc which clearly states readAndDispatch() will \"Reads an event \" which sounds like _single_ event."}

{"id":1211368404,"created_at":"2022-04-21T17:52:45Z","updated_at":"2022-05-05T19:01:16Z","state":"closed","title":"#6536 #10184 macOS Horizontal Scroll Issue","html_url":"https://github.com/dbeaver/dbeaver/pull/16275","body":"The method scrollHorizontally() is called on event SWT.MouseHorizontalWheel. ~~In my testing, it seems like this event is being raised on macOS, but not Windows.~~ The method overrides normal horizontal scrolling and forces either the leftmost or rightmost visible column to be fully visible - depending on whether the user is scrolling to the left or right. This causes scrolling to feel \"jumpy\". If the user has columnScrolling disabled (i.e. Smooth Scrolling enabled), this method probably shouldn't be called.\r\n\r\nThe value for HORZ_SCROLL_INCREMENT is only used if columnScrolling is disabled (Smooth Scrolling enabled) and ~~only~~ appears impacts the UI when responding to a horizontal mouse wheel or if the user clicks the arrows on the scrollbar. The reason for increasing this value is that previously horizontal scroll was moving a column at a time. With this change, the scroll wheel is moving pixel by pixel, and that made scrolling extremely slow. I tested a range of values on a 2019 MacBook Pro and a Microsoft Surface Laptop 4 (in order to test with a Windows Precision Touchpad enabled device), and a value of 12 gave the closest approximation to scrolling in applications like Excel. Behavior was unchanged when using a basic wired mouse."}

org.eclipse.equinox.launcher.Main.main(Main.java:1440)\r\n```\r\n\r\n### Steps to Reproduce\r\n\r\n1. In an existing Feature Modelling project (here named `BerkeleyDB`), create a new folder named `configs`. The project structure now is:\r\n![ProjectViewBefore](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/38729215/138075240-35dcc5dd-c3ea-41ac-90e1-f01bceaac3d6.png)\r\n\r\n2. Right click on the project in the project explorer, then click `Properties` > `FeatureIDE` > `Feature Project`. The text fields `Feature path` and `Source path` are greyed out:\r\n![SetConfigFolder](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/38729215/138075250-e19a4ea0-1be0-4aa6-b462-9f6e66fff9fb.png)\r\n\r\n3. Type `configs` under the `configurations path` text field, and then press `Apply`. This results in the first exception, and also creates the `build` folder.\r\n\r\n4. Create a new configuration named `DBConfig.xml` config. FeatureIDE creates a new folder named `equations`, declares it as configuration folder, and stores `DBConfig.xml` there:\r\n![ActualProjectStructure](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/38729215/138075286-febd56cd-949f-45fc-bb0a-60f5cfaebb2a.png)\r\n\r\n \r\n5. Attempt to change the configuration folder to `configs` as described in Steps 2 and 3, resulting in the second exception."}

{"id":1203430145,"created_at":"2022-04-13T15:03:25Z","updated_at":"2022-05-02T12:13:06Z","state":"closed","title":"SVG images not display in internal preview on Windows","html_url":"https://github.com/de-jcup/eclipse-asciidoctor-editor/issues/394","body":"A meta tag exists in the generated html file `<!--[if IE]><meta http-equiv=\"X-UA-Compatible\" content=\"IE=edge\"><![endif]-->` that should ensure that legacy browser like Internet explorer enables a compatibility mode to workaround the issue. It seems to not work as expected in the case of the SWT internal browser on windows.\r\n\r\nI see two solutions to fix this issue:\r\n* Uncomment the meta tag in the html document [here](https://github.com/de-jcup/eclipse-asciidoctor-editor/blob/master/asciidoctor-editor-plugin/src/main/java-eclipse/de/jcup/asciidoctoreditor/preview/AsciidocEditorPreviewBuildRunnnable.java#L309)\r\n* Use the edge renderer when available (most windows platform nowadays)\r\n\r\nI made a PR for the later: with https://github.com/de-jcup/eclipse-asciidoctor-editor/pull/393"}

It appears that with that there are no issues.\r\n"}
{"id":1218798723,"created_at":"2022-04-28T14:16:22Z","updated_at":"2022-05-02T08:56:08Z","state":"closed","title":"Use java.util.concurrent for Synchronizer.messages #74","html_url":"https://github.com/eclipse-platform/eclipse.platform.swt/pull/77","body":"Synchronizer.messages grew with constant size leading to O(n^2)\r\nperformance for n messages.\r\nAlso the costly \"synchronized\" can be avoided by using\r\njava.util.concurrent DataStructures.\r\n\r\nThe message queue size (which is not O(1) for java.util.concurrent) is\r\nnot needed since only checks for isEmpty() are used."}

Best practice\r\n       is to use the JIRA issue title in the pull request title and in the first line of the commit message.\r\n - [ ] Write a pull request description that is detailed enough to understand what the pull request does, how, and why.\r\n - [ ] Run `mvn clean install apache-rat:check` to make sure basic checks pass. A more thorough check will be performed on your pull request automatically.\r\n - [ ] If you have a group of commits related to the same change, please squash your commits into one and force push your branch using `git rebase -i`. \r\n \r\nTrivial changes like typos do not require a JIRA issue (javadoc, comments...). \r\nIn this case, just format the pull request title like `(DOC) - Add javadoc in SessionManager`.\r\n \r\nIf this is your first contribution, you have to read the [Contribution Guidelines](https://hop.apache.org/community/contributing/)\r\n\r\nIf your pull request is about ~20 lines of code you don't need to sign an [Individual Contributor License Agreement](https://www.apache.org/licenses/icla.pdf) \r\nif you are unsure please ask on the developers list.\r\n\r\nTo make clear that you license your contribution under the [Apache License Version 2.0, January 2004](http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0)\r\nyou have to acknowledge this by using the following check-box.\r\n\r\n - [ ] I hereby declare this contribution to be licenced under the [Apache License Version 2.0, January 2004](http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0)\r\n - [ ] In any other case, please file an [Apache Individual Contributor License Agreement](https://www.apache.org/licenses/icla.pdf)."}

The syntax colouring will gradually disappear as the file is edited, and the only way to resolve is to close the editor and reopen. No change needs to be made in the compare editor for this to happen, just opening the compare seems to be enough. {"id":1004325434,"created_at":"2021-09-22T13:51:52Z","updated_at":"2022-05-24T09:55:44Z","state":"closed","title":"Virtual foreign keys break when changing project navigator view preset from advanced to simple","html_url":"https://github.com/dbeaver/dbeaver/issues/13981","body":"<!--\r\nThank you for reporting an issue.\r\n\r\n*IMPORTANT* -  *before* creating a new issue please look around:\r\n - DBeaver documentation: https://github.com/dbeaver/dbeaver/wiki\r\n and\r\n - open issues in Github tracker: https://github.com/dbeaver/dbeaver/issues\r\n  \r\nIf you cannot find a similar problem, then create a new issue. It helps us to track the most popular requests and fix them faster.\r\n\r\nPlease fill in as much of the template as possible.\r\n-->\r\n\r\n#### System information: \r\n- Operating system (distribution) and version: Windows 10 Pro 20H2\r\n- DBeaver version: 21.2.1\r\n- Additional extensions: Office support, git support, SSHJ, Debug and SVG\r\n\r\n#### Connection specification:\r\n- Database name and version: Postgresql 12.4\r\n- Driver name: PostgreSQL JDBC Driver\r\n- Do you use tunnels or proxies (SSH, SOCKS, etc)? No\r\n\r\n#### Describe the problem you're observing:\r\nIf I create virtual foreign keys on views while on advanced database navigator preset, they work as intended until I change the preset to simple. After that, they seem to lose the reference to the target table.\r\n\r\nUpon examining .dbeaver/data-sources.json, I believe I found the reason. The entity URI is different for virtual foreign keys created on advanced and on simple. On advanced, the \"entity\" json element inside \"foreign-keys\" has this format:\r\n\r\n`database://postgres-jdbc-17c0a78e57b-204d1f0a81d345ce/ajustes2021sbt/org.jkiss.dbeaver.ext.postgresql.model.PostgreSchema/restrito/org.jkiss.dbeaver.ext.postgresql.model.PostgreTable/municipio`\r\n\r\nCreating the same virtual key on simple, it ends up looking like this:\r\n\r\n`database://postgres-jdbc-17c0a78e57b-204d1f0a81d345ce/ajustes2021sbt/restrito/municipio`\r\n\r\nSo, if I'm guessing it right, the virtual key breaks because DBeaver doesn't expect to find the names of the Java classes in the entity URI when the simple navigator preset is active.\r\n\r\n#### Steps to reproduce, if exist:\r\n\r\n1. Edit an existing connection and change its navigator view to the \"advanced\" preset, if it isn't already (it might work the same on custom by leaving both \"Show only schemas and tables\" and \"Hide folders\" unchecked)\r\n2. Open a database view from that connection and, inside the \"Properties\" upper tab, go to the \"Virtual\" lateral tab\r\n3. Click on \"Add\" in the Virtual Foreign Keys quadrant and create a valid virtual foreign key to another table.\r\n4. Edit the connection again and change its navigator view to the \"simple\" preset, (it might work the same on custom by checking both \"Show only schemas and tables\" and \"Hide folders\")\r\n5. Open the view where you created the virtual foreign key. You should be able to verify it doesn't point to the target table.\r\n\r\n\r\n#### Include any warning/errors/backtraces from the logs\r\n<!-- Please, find the short guide how to find logs here: https://github.com/dbeaver/dbeaver/wiki/Log-files -->\r\n`!ENTRY org.jkiss.dbeaver.model 4 0 2021-09-22 09:46:11.233\r\n!MESSAGE Can't find reference node database://postgres-jdbc-17c0a78e57b-204d1f0a81d345ce/ajustes2021sbt/org.jkiss.dbeaver.ext.postgresql.model.PostgreSchema/restrito/org.jkiss.dbeaver.ext.postgresql.model.PostgreTable/municipio for virtual foreign key\r\n!STACK 0\r\norg.jkiss.dbeaver.DBException: Can't find reference node {"id":1142321985,"created_at":"2022-02-18T04:14:14Z","updated_at":"2022-02-18T04:17:05Z","state":"closed","title":"Add a workaround for Apple Silicon","html_url":"https://github.com/diffplug/durian-swt/pull/17","body":"- On Mac Apple Silicon (but not x86_64), SWT Tables and Trees now have giant fat rows ([bugzilla](https://bugs.eclipse.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=575696)).\r\n  - But if you call `setFont(null)` on them, then they have rows the same size as before.\r\n  - We created a new class `SiliconFix` that does nothing on all platforms except Apple Silicon where it calls `setFont(null)`.\r\n  - Wherever a `Table` or `Tree` instantiated (`SmoothTable` and `ColumnFormat`), we use `SiliconFix`.\r\n  - This workaround is perfectly effective as of Eclipse `4.21` and `4.22`, it may become obsolete in a future release.\r\n"}

{"id":523485751,"created_at":"2019-11-15T14:00:58Z","updated_at":"2022-03-07T14:33:12Z","state":"closed","title":"Switch to latest official SWT releases from Maven Central","html_url":"https://github.com/reactor/reactor-addons/issues/216","body":"SWT has started being officially distributed to Maven Central **as of early 2017**.\r\nAs a result, https://maven-eclipse.github.io/maven has not been updated in a while, and the build is currently outdated.\r\n\r\nWe could switch to latest SWT distribution using the `swt platform`, which allows us to declare a dependency to an OS-independent artifact (which in turn declares a dependency to `${osgi.platform}`-dependent jar).\r\n\r\nFor compilation purposes, the osgi.plaftform must be substituted with a locally-relevant os-specific jar, like so:\r\n\r\n```groovy\r\n\tconfigurations.all {\r\n\t\tresolutionStrategy {\r\n\t\t\tdependencySubstitution {\r\n\t\t\t\t// The maven property ${osgi.platform} is not handled by Gradle\r\n\t\t\t\t// so we replace the dependency, using the osgi platform from the project settings\r\n\t\t\t\tsubstitute module('org.eclipse.platform:org.eclipse.swt.${osgi.platform}') with module(\"org.eclipse.platform:org.eclipse.swt.${getSwtPlatform()}:${swtVersionPlatform}\")\r\n\t\t\t}\r\n\t\t}\r\n\t}\r\n\r\n\r\n\tdependencies {\r\n\t\toptional \"org.eclipse.platform:org.eclipse.swt:${swtVersionPlatform}\"\r\n\t}\r\n```\r\n\r\nLatest `swtVersionPlatform` is `3.112.0`. Notice the official Maven Central groupId is `org.eclipse.platform`.\r\n\t\r\n\r\n"}

{"id":209994981,"created_at":"2017-02-24T09:09:03Z","updated_at":"2022-03-16T11:23:41Z","state":"closed","title":"Two Launcher icons in Ubuntu","html_url":"https://github.com/dbeaver/dbeaver/issues/1344","body":"There is a second launcher icon created in ubuntu when you launch the app. The reason for this seems to be that there is an entry called swt created and the  wm_class is SWT. The other launcher entry created is called dbeaver with a class of dbeaver. The best fix would be to change the window class for the application (a property called WM_CLASS) to dbeaver. My fix was to edit the dbeaver.desktop file in /usr/share/applications/dbeaver.desktop and change StartupWMClass to SWT."}

{"id":1111492947,"created_at":"2022-01-22T11:49:50Z","updated_at":"2022-05-07T12:37:39Z","state":"closed","title":"Remove usage of deprecated Observable classes","html_url":"https://github.com/eclipse/gmf-runtime/issues/1","body":"Starting in 2019, the Eclipse Platform has marked several databinding classes as deprecated for removal. See [#546820](https://eclip.se/546820) and [the migration guide](https://help.eclipse.org/latest/index.jsp?topic=%2Forg.eclipse.platform.doc.isv%2Fporting%2Fremovals.html&cp%3D2_3_0).\r\n\r\nThis includes:\r\n\r\n* `org.eclipse.jface.databinding.viewers.ViewersObservables`\r\n* `org.eclipse.jface.databinding.swt.SWTObservables`\r\n* `org.eclipse.core.databinding.beans.BeansObservables`\r\n* `org.eclipse.core.databinding.beans.PojoObservables`\r\n* `org.eclipse.ui.databinding.WorkbenchObservables`\r\n\r\nThey will be completely removed in 2022-09.\r\n\r\nGMF Runtime uses some of these, so must be adapted.\r\n\r\nFrom a quick read of the comments on bug #546820, it seems that the replacements have only been complete starting from around 2020-06 (not sure yet). Depending on how GMF Runtime uses these classes, if we want to be compatible with 2022-09 where these will no longer be available, it might mean we need to drop support for platforms older than ~2020-06 (so that we can use the alternatives).\r\n\r\n"}

{"id":1153952075,"created_at":"2022-02-28T11:05:34Z","updated_at":"2022-03-11T15:05:45Z","state":"closed","title":"Deprecating reactor-extra's Swing/SwtScheduler (removal in 3.6.0)","html_url":"https://github.com/reactor/reactor-addons/issues/273","body":"### Motivation\r\nThe `SwingScheduler` and `SwtScheduler` adapters don't seem to have much traction, as far as we're aware.\r\nThe SWT one is using outdated SWT libraries and complexifies the build infrastructure for little gain.\r\n\r\n(for instance, searching for `reactor.swing.SwingScheduler` results in 2 code hits in all of GitHub. The other one gets 3 hits total...)\r\n\r\n### Deprecation and removal plan\r\n1. Deprecation in 3.4.7 (estimated early March 2022)\r\n2. Removal in 3.6.0 (no planned date, probably late 2023 or late 2024)\r\n~2. Removal in 3.5.0 (estimated last quarter of 2022)~ (see comment below)\r\n\r\n### Additional steps\r\n - [ ] Remove from reference guide appendix in core (this seems to be the main source of results when searching for `SwtScheduler` in all of GitHub btw) => https://github.com/reactor/reactor-core/pull/2959\r\n - [ ] Deprecate in parallel the corresponding extensions in `reactor-kotlin-extensions` => reactor/reactor-kotlin-extensions#38\r\n - [ ] Earlier removal of the very simple extension in `reactor-kotlin-extensions` 1.2.0 (see also reactor/reactor-kotlin-extensions#38)"}

{"id":1010587199,"created_at":"2021-09-29T07:20:01Z","updated_at":"2022-03-14T07:51:39Z","state":"closed","title":"Choose which particular combination of JDK/SWT version to use for the displays of 1.8.2 release","html_url":"https://github.com/gama-platform/gama/issues/3219","body":"It seems that, due to the relative deprecation of JOGL on one hand and the AWT-SWT bridge on the other, which both support our display technologies (OpenGL and Java2D), the choice of the JDK and SWT version on which to run GAMA is particularly sensitive. There have been reports of Java2D displays failing under JDK 11 on macOS, combination of JDK 17 and SWT 2021-06 that make JOGL fail, Java2D and OpenGL failing when used in combination under JDK 11, etc. It is a bit of a mess. \r\n\r\nIn terms of JDK, we can restrict ourselves to JDK 11 (latest version 11.0.12), in its hotspot or J9 incarnation, JDK 15.0.2 (proved to work quite well across the environments) and JDK 17 (which would allow us a long period of tranquility ahead, as it is a LTS version like JDK 11). That makes 4 choices. \r\n\r\nRegarding the OSes, 3 are probably enough (although we might want to include the M1 architecture of macOS or some exotic flavours of Linux): macOS (BigSur, but w. Monterey to test), Windows 10 (with 11 to test), Ubuntu.\r\n\r\nFinally, regarding the SWT versions, we can restrict to 3: 2021-03, 2021-06, 2021-09. \r\n\r\nThat makes around 4 * 3 * 3  = **36 combinations to test.** ! \r\n\r\nShould we split the work ? (answers in comments please) \r\n\r\n"}

{"id":1133585188,"created_at":"2022-02-12T03:25:45Z","updated_at":"2022-02-12T03:51:36Z","state":"closed","title":"Updates to MediaPlayer initialization","html_url":"https://github.com/EroticDevelopment/GuideMe/pull/40","body":"This adds a `LocalDirectoryDiscoveryStrategy` class that allows vljc to search the local lib directory for libvlc in addition to the OS default locations. Additionally, I've removed `SwtEmbeddedMediaPlayer` in favor of the built-in `EmbeddedMediaPlayer` since it now seems possible to bind it to a SWT Video Surface.\r\n\r\nI opted to have VLC search the local lib directory before looking for a Windows install for a couple reasons:\r\n\r\n1. If a user has an old version of VLC installed it could break GuideMe, and the version distributed with the release has been tested to work correctly.\r\n2. If a user doesn't want to use the distributed version for any reason, and instead wants to use their installed version, it's as simple as deleting libvlc from the lib folder or using the Slim release which uses the OS-installed VLC and Java by default."}

Setting implicitExit to false is only needed for Application using FXCanvas in order to prevent JavaFX to terminate when FXCanvas is disposed.\r\n\r\nWith the  current implementation implicitExit=false is set for every application using SWT, but is should only be set when FXCanvas is used."}

{"id":959018494,"created_at":"2021-08-03T11:28:34Z","updated_at":"2022-03-08T09:37:39Z","state":"closed","title":"Java 11","html_url":"https://github.com/eclipse/swtchart/issues/253","body":"https://www.oracle.com/java/technologies/java-se-support-roadmap.html Java 8 is EOL, it is in extended support for commercial customers. https://twitter.com/akurtakov/status/1410577466016649223 did a poll which indicates that Eclipse SWT will drop Java 8 soon as well. There was already interest to compile using the current LTS release Java 11. https://github.com/eclipse/swtchart/pull/110 layed some groundwork to this. Before going even further https://github.com/eclipse/swtchart/issues/252 we should have at least one release targeting current Java LTS."}
{"id":1155781625,"created_at":"2022-03-01T20:25:17Z","updated_at":"2022-04-29T08:50:20Z","state":"closed","title":"Random StringIndexOutOfBoundsException when calling TitleAreaDialog.getMessage","html_url":"https://github.com/eclipse/reddeer/issues/2165","body":"Hi,\r\n\r\nI have a test failing from time to time with this exception:\r\n```text\r\njava.lang.StringIndexOutOfBoundsException: String index out of range: -1\r\n\tat java.base/java.lang.String.substring(String.java:1841)\r\n\tat org.eclipse.reddeer.jface.dialogs.TitleAreaDialog.getMessage(TitleAreaDialog.java:96)\r\n```\r\n\r\nI don't know how to reproduce.\r\n\r\nWe are waiting for an error message to be displayed in our Wizard:\r\n```java\r\n// test code\r\n wizard.next();\r\n new WaitUntil(new DialogMessageIsExpected(wizard, \"Authentication failed\"));\r\n\r\n// utility class\r\npublic class DialogMessageIsExpected extends AbstractWaitCondition {\r\n\r\n  private final TitleAreaDialog dialog;\r\n  private final String expectedMessage;\r\n\r\n  public DialogMessageIsExpected(TitleAreaDialog dialog, String expectedMessage) {\r\n    this.dialog = dialog;\r\n    this.expectedMessage = expectedMessage;\r\n  }\r\n\r\n  @Override\r\n  public boolean test() {\r\n    return dialog.getMessage().equals(expectedMessage);\r\n  }\r\n\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nThe recording of the test shows that the message is present (but possibly the exception already occurred):\r\n![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/281596/156242046-411d986d-69e6-4b27-966a-780e79e992e1.png)\r\n\r\nI guess it could be a race condition in TitleAreaDialog.getMessage:\r\n```java\r\npublic String getMessage() {\r\n\t\tcheckShell();\r\n\t\t// Page Message is 5th Text within first Composite of TitleAreaDialog and is inactive \r\n\t\tControl textControl = handler.getChildren(getShellComposite())[4];\r\n\t\tString message = \"\";\r\n// -> At this moment the message and image are still empty\r\n\t\tif (textControl instanceof org.eclipse.swt.widgets.Label) {\r\n\t\t\tmessage = getMessageLabel(textControl).getText(); // message = \"\"\r\n\t\t} else {\r\n\t\t\tmessage = getMessageText(textControl).getText();\r\n\t\t}\r\n// --> Here the message and image are changed to Error icon + \"Authentication failed\", but the message variable has already been assigned\r\n\t\tif(getMessageImage() != null){ // image is not null\r\n\t\t\tmessage = message.substring(1); // StringIndexOutOfBoundsException\r\n\t\t}\r\n\t\treturn message;\r\n\t}\r\n```\r\n\r\nIf I'm correct, a fix could be to add a guard before calling `message.substring(1)`:\r\n\r\n```java\r\n\t\tif(getMessageImage() != null && message.length > 0){ //if image is shown TitleAreaDialog adds whitespace before message\r\n\t\t\tmessage = message.substring(1);\r\n\t\t}\r\n```\r\n\r\nExcept if you can think of an atomic way of getting both the image and the message at the same time?"}

{"id":493148582,"created_at":"2019-09-13T05:53:39Z","updated_at":"2022-03-06T06:15:17Z","state":"closed","title":"Remove JavaFX from platform","html_url":"https://github.com/eclipse/chemclipse/issues/8","body":"JavaFX is no longer supported by Oracle, hard to integrate (requires special handling to work in build and OSGi runtime), is not included in standard OpenJDK builds and has produced several issues (freeze on windows) in the past.\r\n\r\nBeside that, embedding another UI Framework into Checmclipse makes it look different in that places from the normal SWT-style.\r\n\r\nBecause of that, we should reduce/replace javaFX usage and finally remove FX support from the platform at all."}

{"id":1153754152,"created_at":"2022-02-28T07:36:28Z","updated_at":"2022-03-03T03:44:48Z","state":"closed","title":"Attempting to run in archlinux results in the software crashing","html_url":"https://github.com/Querz/mcaselector/issues/339","body":"Java Version: `jre-openjdk 17.0.3.u3-1`\r\nJavaFX Version: `java-openjfx 17.0.3.u0-1`\r\n\r\n- as you can see, near enough the same version that it should work fine\r\n  \r\nMcaSelector Version - mcaselector-1.17.2.jar\r\n\r\nCommandline to launch \r\n`java -jar mcaselector-1.17.2.jar --module-path \"/usr/lib/jvm/java-17-openjdk/lib/\" --add-modules ALL-MODULE-PATH`\r\n\r\n\r\nThe Software crashes with this response:\r\n\r\n`failed to create directory /etc/xdg/mcaselector: /etc/xdg/mcaselector(AccessDeniedException)`\r\n`failed to create directory /etc/xdg/mcaselector: /etc/xdg/mcaselector(AccessDeniedException)`\r\n`[17:26:05.973] error: missing mode`\r\n\r\nFrom these lines alone, This appears to be trying to use the system default xdg location for xdg configurations as specified in `$XDG_CONFIG_DIRS`  (which if unspecified in the environment variables, should default to `/etc/xdg/`) instead it should default to the user configuration directory as specified in `$XDG_CONFIG_HOME`  which if unspecified should default to `$HOME/.config/` - with `$HOME` being an environment variable defined upon user login to identify what and where the user's home directory is.\r\n\r\n`$HOME/.config` is pretty much the linux version of `%appdata%` with the alternative directory being `$HOME/.local/share/`\r\n\r\nAs you can see, this is resulting in a permissions error - the permissions of `/etc/xdg/` make it so that that directory can only be written by its owner, which is the root user, or the system administrator account, and it makes no sense to write files that have to do with a piece of user software in a system configuration directory\r\n\r\nI have seen this issue pop up in closed bug reports like report #285 - but this is unique as i am not using an incorrect or incompatible version of java or javafx - both of these are the latest from the official archlinux repository and should work fine together. It might have something to do with my XDG desktop configuration (running XFCE4) but all my XDG configs are the default for this window manager anyway."}

textViewer implementation is from SourceViewer from an ITextViewer parameter\r\n org.eclipse.jface.text.source.ISourceViewer extends  org.eclipse.jface.text.source.ITextViewer\r\nImplementing Classes:org.eclipse.jface.text.source.SourceViewer\r\n\r\n\r\n`Field field = SourceViewer.class.getDeclaredField(\"fPresentationReconciler\");`\r\nThis doesn't check that that field actually exists on textViewer before trying to get textViewer's field value, nor that textViewer is an instance of SourceViewer ( ISourceViewer can be implemented elsewhere)\r\nI think there should be a  check that textViewer is an instance of SourceViewer but also that field isn't null.\r\n```\r\nIPresentationReconciler presentationReconciler = (IPresentationReconciler) field.get(textViewer);\r\nreturn presentationReconciler instanceof TMPresentationReconciler ? (TMPresentationReconciler) presentationReconciler : null;\r\n```\r\ninstead I think that the code should have \r\n`IPresentationReconciler presentationReconciler = field == null ? null : (IPresentationReconciler) field.get(textViewer);`"}

{"id":1145621011,"created_at":"2022-02-21T10:40:11Z","updated_at":"2022-02-25T10:17:58Z","state":"closed","title":"Significant target-resolution runtime regression","html_url":"https://github.com/eclipse/tycho/issues/670","body":"As reported in https://github.com/eclipse/tycho/discussions/651#discussioncomment-2218409 the initial resolution of the target platform is magnitudes slower with the current Tycho `2.7.0-SNAPSHOT` compared to `2.6.0`, in my case ~30min compared to ~30sec before.\r\n\r\nI have the impression that each dependency of each plug-in being built is fully fetched from a mirror again, even if it was already fetched for another plug-in which has the same dependency in the same Maven build. Therefore the runtime becomes linear to the number of references to dependencies and not only linear to the cardinality of the set of dependencies (which would be relatable).\r\nFurthermore the dependencies should not be re-downloaded on each build which happens often (or maybe always, I cannot say that clearly from the print-out).\r\n\r\nPlease find attached a relativly small reproducer that contains three identical plug-ins that have the same dependencies:\r\n[tycho-2-7.zip](https://github.com/eclipse/tycho/files/8108483/tycho-2-7.zip)\r\n"}

{"id":713764366,"created_at":"2020-10-02T16:52:38Z","updated_at":"2022-01-21T03:03:50Z","state":"closed","title":"Compiling on Raspberry Pi","html_url":"https://github.com/AppleCommander/AppleCommander/issues/45","body":"The current code does not compile on Pi/Arm. It can be made to compile by taking the following actions:\r\n\r\nOn Pi (Raspbian), issue command:\r\nsudo apt-get install libswt-gtk-3-java\r\n\r\nMake the following edits to build.gradle in repo:\r\nLine 111:\r\n- compile \"org.eclipse.swt:org.eclipse.swt.gtk.linux.x86_64:$swtVersion\"\r\n+ include '/usr/share/java/swt-gtk-3.8.jar'\r\n\r\nLine 113:\r\n- appendix 'linux64-gtk'\r\n+ appendix 'linuxarm-gtk'\r\n\r\nNote: This approach results in a package that will compile and run, but GUI does not actually list file contents when opening an Apple II disk image. Also, a linux-arm clause would obviously need to be added to the build.gradle file, so that the linux scenario would continue to build for x86. It may also be possible to issue a compile option instead of the include (so that apt-get install isn't necessary), but I wasn't able to track down a URL that would be referenced for the Arm build of SWT-Gtk."}

{"id":926161265,"created_at":"2021-06-21T12:21:44Z","updated_at":"2021-11-18T16:03:31Z","state":"closed","title":"Migrated eclipse.ui/SWT dependencies.","html_url":"https://github.com/eclipse/elk/pull/762","body":"The core.service plugin bundles functionality that is currently Eclipse dependent, but could be used outside of an Eclipse context (such as the DiagramLayoutEngine). I suggest to split the core.service plugin in an Eclipse dependent and independent part.\r\n\r\nIdeally, we would want to do this also for downstream projects. For Klighd we decided it would be best to mock SWT und eclipse.ui instead via package dependencies and a mock plugin. The other alternative to deeclipsify Klighd would be to do something similar to the changes here and split every synthesis into three parts, which is why we don't want to do this now and try to mock it instead.\r\n\r\nThe DiagramLayoutEngine is currently used for interactive layout using a language server (or KIELER). However, we do not need the eclipse dependencies in that case. Moreover, we are working on a general diagram server/VSCode plugin and others to be able to use this too without understanding our whole build infrastructure. Currently, we have to supply three language servers for this. With an eclipse independent ELK (and Klighd) this does not have to be the case.\r\n\r\ntldr: We need the not-eclipse-dependent functions and currently have dependencies to eclipse, which we start to elimate beginning with ELK.\r\n\r\nSigned-off-by: Soeren Domroes <sdo@informatik.uni-kiel.de>"}

{"id":1164270206,"created_at":"2022-03-09T18:04:14Z","updated_at":"2022-04-11T16:48:45Z","state":"closed","title":"Verification with nuXmv via Kieler runs indefinitely on Windows 10 for models that generate long traces ","html_url":"https://github.com/kieler/semantics/issues/8","body":"When verifying .sctx model properties in Kieler with nuXmv, Kieler starts up nuXmv as a separate thread, reads the output, and provides the user with the result and other data.\r\n\r\nDepending on the verification command, model, property etc., the output to be consumed can vary in length. For most models/properties that result in short nuXmv output, everything works as expected on Windows 10 with Java 11 (openJDK).\r\n\r\nGenerally, if a verification attempt is actively running in nuXmv, we can see some CPU activity in the task manager. Once the verification has completed, CPU activity reduces noticably.              \r\nNow, for some models, the verification never terminates _in Kieler_. We can see that nuXmv is doing no more work after some time, as the CPU is idle, yet Kieler shows that the verification is still running. The same model/verification has no problem finishing when run on Linux.\r\n\r\nNuXmv by itself does not seem to be the issue: We can stop the non-completing Kieler-Verification with the stop button and open the SMV that nuXmv/Kieler was using via the three-dot-menu > \"Open model checker model\". We can save the content of this smv-model as a file somewhere, and open a console in the folder that now contains the `.smv` file. Now, we run NuXmv like Kieler does, in the interactive mode (`nuXmv -int model.smv`). In the interactive mode, we use the same commands that were configured in Kieler (Verification table > three-dot menu > Options > Edit SMV commands). We run the verification - and after some time, the verification finishes, and we can quit from nuXmv.\r\n\r\nThe question(s) now is/are: Does Kieler not recognize that nuXmv finished? Does nuXmv finish at all when run via Kieler? Does Kieler see that nuXmv finished, but does it ignore that? etc....\r\n\r\n\r\nI investigated this issue briefly during last summer. If I recall correctly, the problem was that reading from the process output works slightly differently on Posix vs. other thread models, even with the whole `write once, run anywhere` Java idea.           \r\n\r\nKieler does read from the nuXmv output buffer. See RunSMVProcessor ( package de.cau.cs.kieler.verification.processors.nuxmv), method `runModelChecker`:            \r\nIn the for-loop starting on line 147, each command specified by the user (or the default) gets entered, one per loop iteration. After each command input (line 150, 151), Kieler waits for process output (L158) and consumes it (L160). The method waitForOutput checks the availability of output about every millisecond (de.cau.cs.kieler.verification.processors.ProcessExtensions -> waitForOutput). It returns once output becomes available.           \r\nThe method readInputStream is then called to consume the nuXmv output (de.cau.cs.kieler.verification.processors.ProcessExtensions -> readInputStream). It reads _as long as there is something to read_, i.e. as long as the input stream says so.             \r\nThis is the point where the problem occurs (on Windows at least): In some situations, nuXmv takes some time between putting out \"updates\" of the verification. `inputStream.available` in `readInputStream` thus returns 0, as no new output is available to read. We stop reading from the output. If this happens in the last for-loop iteration, and nuXmv is not yet finished, there's a problem: The next command is waitForTermination - it does what it says, and does _not_ read the output. BUT: The last command sent to nuXmv, which will be evaluated after verification, is \"quit\". So nuXmv _should_ stop after some time, after which the check `proc.isAlive` in waitForOutput _should_ return false - waitForTermination would thus return.            \r\nIn Linux, this works just fine. However, on Windows, processes that are started like the one here have a size-limit for the output buffer. If the output buffer is not being read from regularly, it will be full after some time/number of bytes being written to it. If that happens, the process will **block**. It still counts as _alive_, which is why waitForTermination/ `proc.isAlive` wouldn't notice this. Consequently, Kieler is waiting for nuXmv to terminate, but nuXmv can't terminate, because it can't write to its output buffer.\r\n\r\nThe Javadoc for `Process` says:\r\n\r\n>    Because some native platforms only provide limited buffer size for standard input and output streams, failure to promptly write the input stream or read the output stream of the subprocess may cause the subprocess to block, and even deadlock.\r\n\r\nSo this is probably what's happening here. Buffer size on Windows may vary, I've seen some people state ~8192 bytes; on most Linux distros and MacOs the limit is usually 65536 bytes from what I found. The model that I was testing with produces an output of roughly 48 000 bytes in size - so we're not too far off locking up the buffer on Linux as well.\r\n\r\n\r\nI will be working on a solution that continues consuming the output buffer whilst also checking for a cancel request from the user. Basically, waitForTermination and readInputStream in one.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, I will add a comment with \"Steps-to-reproduce\" information in the very near future."}

{"id":426442797,"created_at":"2019-03-28T11:32:43Z","updated_at":"2022-02-28T14:37:34Z","state":"closed","title":"[Native] Scaling issue on Windows 10 with HiDPI and Java 10","html_url":"https://github.com/jzy3d/jzy3d-api/issues/101","body":"Chart is not scaled properly under Windows 10 with HiDPI monitors & Java 10-11 : chart get displayed half size on a corner for HiDPI windows stations on native charts ([EmulGL](https://github.com/jzy3d/jzy3d-api/tree/master/jzy3d-emul-gl) is a very good **portability workaround**).\r\n\r\n![lccmonleccddelli](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/2334960/55154621-8eb7f000-5155-11e9-9a43-70f38e2a87c9.png)\r\n\r\n\r\n### Cases\r\n\r\nAll rendering glitches under Windows 10 with an HiDPI monitor are below with a demo programs reference from [jzy3d-tutorials](https://github.com/jzy3d/jzy3d-api/tree/master/jzy3d-tutorials).\r\n\r\n###### Case 1 : half chart on screen\r\nHappens for the following `IPainterFactory`\r\n- AWT (`SurfaceDemoAWT`)\r\n- AWTNewt (`SurfaceDemoAWTNewt`)\r\n- SWTBridge (`SurfaceDemoSWTBridge`)\r\n\r\n###### Case 2 : chart full screen but not using HiDPI capabilities\r\nChart are displayed on complete canvases but do not make use of HiDPI capabilities which makes the chart ugly relative to other applications displayed on the same monitor.\r\n- Swing (`SurfaceDemoSwing`)\r\n\r\n###### Case 3 : properly working\r\n- SWT (`SurfaceDemoSWT`)\r\n\r\n###### Workaround : use EmulGL\r\n- AWT (`SurfaceDemoEmulGL`)\r\n\r\nIt turns out to be a known problem with the way the JVM supports HiDPI, which is [discussed in JOGL forum](http://forum.jogamp.org/JOGL-broken-with-JRE-gt-8-and-Windows-window-scaling-td4039122.html).\r\n\r\nWorkarounds are proposed [here](https://superuser.com/questions/988379/how-do-i-run-java-apps-upscaled-on-a-high-dpi-display/1207925#1207925).\r\n\r\n"}

{"id":1069480642,"created_at":"2021-12-02T12:15:31Z","updated_at":"2022-02-01T20:07:10Z","state":"closed","title":"CDateTime does not notify focusLost","html_url":"https://github.com/eclipse/nebula/issues/430","body":"A FocusListener attached to CDateTime is not notified about a focusLost when the focus changes from the CDateTime to a non-VControl widget. Apparently the VTracker.setFocusControl(VControl control) ignores the possibility that control (which is received by VTracker.getVControl(...) in the FocusIn case in the VTracker.filter) may have been a standard SWT widget instead of a VControl-based widget.\r\nI assume this bug was introduced in https://github.com/eclipse/nebula/commit/b9129cd66a3cf3fb7380cc4b996e354b95965016. Thus, the fix should especially not re-introduce the old bug https://bugs.eclipse.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=476035.\r\n\r\n\r\nThe attached sample application [CDateTimeFocus.zip](https://github.com/eclipse/nebula/files/7641727/CDateTimeFocus.zip) demonstrates that error. Test steps:\r\n- Focus the left CDateTime widget\r\n- Press the \"Any button\" -> on standard out no focus lost message is printed\r\n- Focus the left CDateTime widget again\r\n- Focus the right CDateTime widget -> on standard out a focus lost message is printed\r\n\r\n"}

{"id":1039925916,"created_at":"2021-10-29T21:02:32Z","updated_at":"2021-10-29T23:46:42Z","state":"closed","title":"Fixes to new remoteinstall project","html_url":"https://github.com/bndtools/bnd/pull/4920","body":"Eclipse showed a number of compile warning. This is partly due to the\r\ncode and partly due to the missing Eclipse settings. The code is\r\nformatted with the settings.\r\n\r\nWe also make sure org.eclipse.swt is listed in -buildpath before the\r\nswt fragment (which hold the proper code). This makes sure the\r\nimport package clauses reference the org.eclipse.swt bundle symbolic\r\nname and not the fragments. We also add the bundle to\r\nbndtools.core.test bndruns to make sure it resolves in the constructed\r\nEclipse instance.\r\n\r\nWe replace use of GSON with JSONCodec to avoid an external dependency.\r\n\r\nOther fixes are also included in this PR."}

{"id":1147364052,"created_at":"2022-02-22T21:02:02Z","updated_at":"2022-02-24T10:18:01Z","state":"closed","title":"DBeaver ignores fragments in links","html_url":"https://github.com/dbeaver/dbeaver/issues/15599","body":"#### System information: \r\n\r\nManjaro Linux\r\nDBeaver version 21.3.3.202201242151\r\n\r\n#### Connection specification:\r\nSQL Lite\r\n\r\n#### Describe the problem you're observing:\r\nDBeaver automatically shows a small url arrow in columns containing urls. This is a nice feature that makes links clickable and open them in the default browser.\r\n\r\nHowever, the fragment part (after the hash #) is ignored. So the link https://example.com/test#123 will open https://example.com/test in the browser. Since many single page applications (SPA) rely on fragment links, these might not work when opened from DBeaver.\r\n\r\n#### Steps to reproduce, if exist:\r\nInsert https://example.com/test#123 in any text column and click on the little url arrow.\r\n\r\n"}

{"id":1065120650,"created_at":"2021-11-27T19:58:19Z","updated_at":"2021-12-02T06:24:27Z","state":"closed","title":"Replace the statusbar LED GIFs with PNGs","html_url":"https://github.com/BiglySoftware/BiglyBT/pull/2343","body":"I tried out the dark theme support recently, and discovered that while it mostly looks great, the \"LED\" GIFs used for the NAT and Ratio state indicators in the statusbar have incredibly poor transparency which makes them look like trash. They show massive amounts of speckling around the edges, against a dark background.\r\n\r\nHere's how they look against white:\r\n\r\n![gif_light](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/538020/143720392-4dec34a3-c85f-4aa5-9c6b-459d7dde36cb.png)\r\n\r\nAnd against black:\r\n\r\n![gif_dark](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/538020/143720416-20d28cf8-9783-4d59-92b5-871c8d4f4bd3.png)\r\n\r\nEw, right? So, I drew new ones, as transparent PNGs, with specific focus on making sure the transparency of the pixels around the edge didn't bias the image towards any particular background color, and therefore look ugly against a _different_ background color.\r\n\r\nMy replacements, against white:\r\n\r\n![png_light](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/538020/143720454-943f38a9-c84a-4b9a-b062-bcbaddf79a19.png)\r\n\r\nAnd against black:\r\n\r\n![png_dark](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/538020/143720460-e5357317-4354-483b-819b-5e1a6804ff60.png)\r\n\r\n\r\nI don't _love_ them, and I think the gray and yellow could both be \"brighter\", but I figured I'd submit this first pass. I can make adjustments if anyone would prefer, just let me know.\r\n\r\nThis PR installs the new images into the `uis/src/com/biglybt/ui/icons/` directory (named `redled.png` for the `redled.gif` replacement, and so on...), and it changes the strings in `uis/src/com/biglybt/ui/icons/icons.properties` to point to the new icon files. Which I **think** is all that's necessary to make use of them, instead of the previous GIF icons? Please correct me if I'm wrong.\r\n\r\nI didn't delete the `*led.gif` files. No real reason, I just didn't. Presumably they'll no longer get included in the build since they're not in the properties file, so they're only taking up space in the repo, not the JAR.\r\n"}

{"id":1051400838,"created_at":"2021-11-11T22:09:04Z","updated_at":"2021-11-12T14:29:43Z","state":"closed","title":"central: Refresh workspace inside bndLock for cnf change","html_url":"https://github.com/bndtools/bnd/pull/4944","body":"If a change to cnf was detected, we called workspace refresh without\r\nregard to any running builders. This caused issues where the workspace\r\nrefresh closed repos while a builder was running.\r\n\r\nWe now refresh the workspace while holding the bndLock. We use a job\r\nto handle this in case we need to wait for the lock and don't want to\r\nblock the notification (which could be the main) thread.\r\n"}

{"id":1083342996,"created_at":"2021-12-17T15:00:31Z","updated_at":"2021-12-20T16:25:26Z","state":"closed","title":"Enhance colors of the graph editor and make them more colorblind-friendly","html_url":"https://github.com/hexatomic/hexatomic/pull/365","body":"<!-- Please refer to our contributing documentation for any questions on submitting a pull request, or let us know here if you need any help. -->\r\n\r\n## Pull request type\r\n\r\n<!-- Please try to limit your pull request to one type, submit multiple pull requests if needed. \r\nChoose one of the following types (you can copy and paste them if you like)\r\n\r\n- Bugfix\r\n- Feature\r\n- Code style update (formatting, renaming)\r\n- Refactoring (no functional changes, no API changes)\r\n- Build related changes\r\n- Documentation content changes\r\n- Other (please describe it)\r\n\r\n--> \r\n\r\nFeature\r\n\r\n## What is the current behavior?\r\n<!-- Please describe the current behavior that you are modifying, or link to a relevant issue. -->\r\n\r\nThe old colors in the graph editor where inconsistent with the grid editor (e.g. tokens were light green and spans hat no color) and also very eye-stressing. No consideration was done to whether the colors are colorblind-friendly.\r\n\r\nIssue Number: #173 \r\n\r\n\r\n## What is the new behavior?\r\n<!-- Please describe the behavior or changes that are being added by this PR. -->\r\n\r\n- Added all colors from <http://www.cookbook-r.com/Graphs/Colors_(ggplot2)/#a-colorblind-friendly-palette> as SWT constants in the `ColorPalette` class in the core package\r\n- Use these colors in the graph editor\r\n- Change the spanning node annotation name color to greenish (as in the grid editor)\r\n- Use plain white nodes with black text for the token (as in the grid editor) and a grey border\r\n- Use border and line styles (dashed, dotted, solid) to distinguish the annotation node/edge types in addition to the color\r\n\r\n![graph-viewer](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/2168104/146779383-7791e52e-ef43-4671-8c5f-9c75193e328e.png)\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n## Does this introduce a breaking change?\r\n\r\n<!-- If this introduces a breaking change, please describe the impact and migration path for existing applications below. -->\r\n\r\nN/A\r\n\r\n## Other information\r\n\r\n<!-- Any other information that is important to this PR such as screenshots of how the component looks before and after the change. -->\r\nThe grid editor does not use the color palette yet, but the green is similar enough so it is clear it refers to spans in both cases.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n## Pull request checklist\r\n\r\nPlease check if your PR fulfills the following requirements:\r\n- [X] Tests for the changes have been added **or** the PR is neither a bug fix nor a feature\r\n- [X] Docs have been reviewed and added / updated if needed **or** the PR is neither a bug fix nor a feature\r\n- [X] The *Unreleased* section in CHANGELOG.md has been amended to reflect the changes in this PR if needed\r\n- [X] Build (`mvn verify`) was run locally and any changes were pushed\r\n- [X] The pull request is against the correct branch (`master` for bug fixes, `develop` for new functionality)\r\n- [X] [Dependencies and citation templates](https://github.com/hexatomic/hexatomic/tree/develop/releng/templates) have been updated where necessary **or** there are no new dependencies\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n# Checklist for maintainers\r\n\r\n## Releases\r\n\r\n- Do **NOT** push the green merge button on GitHub.  \r\nFollow the latest version of the [developer/maintainer docs](https://hexatomic.github.io/hexatomic/dev/) for making releases.\r\n- Check that license and citation information for dependencies are complete (each dependency has a folder in `/THIRD-PARTY/`).\r\n"}

{"id":1191056133,"created_at":"2022-04-03T21:51:55Z","updated_at":"2022-05-13T20:26:06Z","state":"closed","title":"[Feature Request] Force Post-Completion Checking to Occur BEFORE Post-Completion Moving","html_url":"https://github.com/BiglySoftware/BiglyBT/issues/2514","body":"Current behavior in the (excellent and much appreciated) client is unpredictable as to what order checking and moving occur after a download completes. Sometimes it checks then moves, sometimes it moves then checks, sometimes it starts to check then moves and then finishes checking. It all seems to depend on how many torrents are being checked/moved/etc. at that particular moment and what combination of relevant settings one has enabled.\r\n\r\nAn issue therefore arises as I have BiglyBT set to recheck after completion and to move torrents on completion to a network share. When moving occurs before the check I end up with extra network traffic clogging the pipes as the check has to be done over the network instead of off the local drive. This can seriously slow down everything - downloading, seeding, moving, and checking - when there are lots of downloads completing, moving, and checking all at the same time.\r\n\r\nThe logical solution would be to force the program to check before moving on completion. Barring that, an option to force that behavior would be greatly appreciated.\r\n\r\nThanks!\r\n"}

{"id":674293128,"created_at":"2020-08-06T12:57:24Z","updated_at":"2021-12-01T19:02:03Z","state":"closed","title":"More compact tree node indentation","html_url":"https://github.com/HPCToolkit/hpcviewer.e4/issues/4","body":"Feedback from @martyitz :\r\n\r\n> In the viewer, a lot of nodes are inserted between a function and the function it calls, including loop and line information.\r\n> That leads to very deep displays, and I wonder if that’s the best way to guide the user.  I would suggest some way to exclude\r\n> those lines easily.  I think they usually represent noise to the user, making it difficult to see the call chain in terms of functions,\r\n> which is what the user understands.  The deep displays also lead to too much indentation in the Scope column."}

{"id":778253945,"created_at":"2021-01-04T17:44:35Z","updated_at":"2021-10-11T17:59:40Z","state":"closed","title":"Update client assemblies to package newer Eclipse libraries that work…","html_url":"https://github.com/pentaho/pentaho-kettle/pull/7807","body":"Update client assemblies to package newer Eclipse libraries that work better on current Mac OS versions.  This includes updates to SWT, JFace, Eclipse common and command runtimes.\r\n\r\nThere are still some issues relative to theming on Mac OS such that it is not always easy to read some text, but at least it avoid the exceptions that occur when updating the SWT version without updating JFace and the core runtime libraries along with it.\r\n\r\nIt should be noted that this does not update the dependencies for the various Kettle libraries since they appear to be the same from a compilation perspective.  It merely overrides the versions that are captured via the assembly into the community edition client zip file.\r\n\r\nFinally, it should be noted that these changes also remove the old 32 bit versions of the SWT libraries as they appear to be unsupported at this point and generally speaking, most people should be on a 64 bit OS.\r\n"}

Wenn ein Attribut Einstellungen hat, dann wird in dieser Spalte ein Button sichtbar. Klickt man darauf öffnet sich ein Dialog in dem die Attributs-Einstellungen sicht- & änderbar sind. {"id":1007945344,"created_at":"2021-09-27T10:00:27Z","updated_at":"2021-09-28T13:58:47Z","state":"closed","title":"Workaround fix for JVM Crash Issue while refreshing 'ProblemTreeViewer'","html_url":"https://github.com/bndtools/bnd/pull/4862","body":"This workaround ensures that the action is performed on the display thread properly by rescheduling it on the display thread. Note that, previously it was also executed on the display thread, but underlying SWT/JFace didn't submit the task properly to the display thread. That's why, this MR ensures that we submit the task properly (or explicitly) to the display thread. The bug still exists in the SWT/JFace which needs to be fixed. Other plugins using `getTreeViewer().refresh()` from `PackageExplorerPart` are prone to crash the JVM as well.\r\n\r\nFixes #4854"}

{"id":970118099,"created_at":"2021-08-13T06:57:11Z","updated_at":"2021-08-13T07:35:44Z","state":"closed","title":"SWT key handling on macOS","html_url":"https://github.com/eclipse/swtchart/issues/258","body":"Some users have reported strange behavior regarding the range and distance selection on macOS. A test case to inspect it has been created here:\r\n\r\n[#257](https://github.com/eclipse/swtchart/issues/257)\r\n\r\nAs it turned out, instead of using SWT.CTRL, SWT.MOD1 shall be used instead. This has been also described here:\r\nhttps://bugs.eclipse.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=463130#c7\r\n\r\nThe following mappings shall be replaced:\r\n\r\n- SWT.CTRL -> SWT.MOD1\r\n- SWT.SHIFT -> SWT.MOD2\r\n- SWT.ALT -> SWT.MOD3\r\n\r\nSee documentation in [SWT.java](https://git.eclipse.org/c/platform/eclipse.platform.swt.git/tree/bundles/org.eclipse.swt/Eclipse%20SWT/common/org/eclipse/swt/SWT.java).\r\n"}

{"id":1026266457,"created_at":"2021-10-14T11:10:18Z","updated_at":"2021-10-14T12:27:34Z","state":"closed","title":"Work around intermittent crash when saving snapshot from Data Browser","html_url":"https://github.com/ControlSystemStudio/cs-studio/pull/2710","body":"Our users report that intermittently CSS will crash when saving a snapshot from the data browser.\r\n\r\nThe output is\r\n\r\n```[xcb] Unknown request in queue while dequeuing\r\n[xcb] Most likely this is a multi-threaded client and XInitThreads has not been called\r\n[xcb] Aborting, sorry about that.\r\njava: xcb_io.c:165: dequeue_pending_request: Assertion `!xcb_xlib_unknown_req_in_deq' failed.\r\n```\r\n\r\nWe deduced this is another manifrstation of the issue described here https://github.com/ControlSystemStudio/cs-studio/issues/2660 and here https://github.com/ControlSystemStudio/phoebus/issues/705\r\n\r\nThis PR implements a similar workaround for the Save Snapshot. i.e.  to create the image on the UI thread.\r\n\r\nThe [SWT issue is still open on eclipse.org](https://bugs.eclipse.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=568859). One commenter reports that a later Eclipse version no longer has this behaviour, so it is possible that it will not be fixed in 2020-12. I expect that for us to upgrade the Eclipse version is a very big task and therefore prefer to implement this workaround in order to fix this crash for an upcoming DLS release.\r\n\r\ncc @rjwills28 \r\n"}

{"id":1067293126,"created_at":"2021-11-30T14:20:20Z","updated_at":"2021-12-02T06:22:06Z","state":"closed","title":"[Question] View and Controllers design","html_url":"https://github.com/gluonhq/ignite/issues/20","body":"Hi folks, I hope you don't mind me using this as a question spot, could not really find a place to ask for guidance.\r\n\r\nAs I design my app (I'm not a javafx person, but I wrote swing/swt and android apps in the past). I have been thinking about some design choices.\r\n\r\nFirst I really enjoy ignite, but I'm having a hard time coming to terms with the FXMLView and Controller overlap in some cases, please allow me to elaborate.\r\n\r\nWhen my view is mostly driven by FXML that FXMLView is really a nice fit, although I find it to be mostly an empty shell class, since all logic is within the controller.\r\n\r\nBut I started to bump into cases where FXML is not enough, and what I'm usually doing is having a root container on my fxml file, and the controller defining a series of view elements (such as Controls). \r\n\r\nAnd this is where my problem lies, I can't really declare the controls on the view, because the controller will have no access to them. But it seems that in this case the View is kinda redundant, and I should just have View that acts as a controller too handling all the logic.\r\n\r\nAny thoughts on this? I thought this to be an interesting topic for beginners like myself.\r\n\r\nCheers"}

{"id":997351186,"created_at":"2021-09-15T17:44:09Z","updated_at":"2021-09-16T03:11:30Z","state":"closed","title":"Revive IFDSExplorerExample","html_url":"https://github.com/wala/WALA/pull/975","body":"Fixes #921 \r\n\r\nPreviously we did not test that the SWT-related code in `com.ibm.wala.ide.tests` actually ran correctly, and we ended up with some classpath issues not detected by just building the code (e.g., a dependence that required Java 11).  This PR fixes these issues, and adds a unit test so we don't regress in the future.\r\n\r\nAlso, we add a Gradle task to run `IFDSExplorerExample` to make it easier for others to try out in the future."}

{"id":1077503476,"created_at":"2021-12-11T10:59:54Z","updated_at":"2022-01-21T10:17:42Z","state":"closed","title":"Image loading issue at Gamebo's Omega Mission","html_url":"https://github.com/hex007/freej2me/issues/117","body":"The game _Omega Mission_ by Gamebo (tested JAR md5: `9f353fbf1c7bf54aa306ce63ed7f1fd6`) crashes during initialization in FreeJ2ME due to it passing a damaged PNG image to `javax.microedition.lcdui.Image.createImage(byte[], int, int)`. The images load fine in KEmulator and a Nokia 7230\r\n\r\nTracing it back, such image is stored into a packed resources file (`/1` into the JAR) and read into a byte array by a custom routine at the game (`GameMidlet.a(String,int,int)`) which uses a DataInputStream to read the file from the JAR then pass it to createImage().\r\nThe image data is 15KB but it appears to be truncated at around ~7KB as passed to createImage()\r\n![shot](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/57576450/145673565-b2f728ff-8dd6-40af-9626-fdd564eada86.png)\r\n_A small visual treat to spice up the issue_\r\n\r\nThe game expects a single call to `DataInputStream.read(byte[] b, int off, int len)` to return all the data and ignores its return value, while according to the javadocs it appears not to neccesarily do so (https://nikita36078.github.io/J2ME_Docs/docs/midp-2.0/java/io/InputStream.html#read(byte[],%20int,%20int)) _(I'm unsure about it, though. Don't clearly understand when it's supposed to return less data than available and when to block)_\r\n\r\nI think the FreeJ2ME-passed InputStream object doesn't returns all the available data from the stream on a `read(byte[] b, int off, int len)` call, behaviour this game appears to rely on. The game code is obfuscated and also performs an intermediate transform on the data, though. Will try setting up a small test MIDlet instead to be able to better peek into what's going on.\r\n\r\nThank you!\r\n"}

{"id":990154130,"created_at":"2021-09-07T16:26:23Z","updated_at":"2021-09-09T11:13:42Z","state":"closed","title":"Mapping have to be modified from the outside","html_url":"https://github.com/eclipse/swtchart/issues/265","body":"The mapping feature is a bit unintuitive. It maps settings and stores them for later reuse, even after the panel has been destroyed. Developers and users are forced to use this (anti-)feature as there is no way to turn it off without breaking it. Every SWT Chart UI action will internally  update the mappings:\r\n\r\nhttps://github.com/eclipse/swtchart/blob/a6dda0bbfa38934a5a9c6324bcf94bc24687fbd9/org.eclipse.swtchart.extensions/src/org/eclipse/swtchart/extensions/menu/legend/SetDescriptionAction.java#L81-L83\r\n\r\nConsumer of SWT Chart are allowed to change the values, but cannot update the mapping, leaving the chart labels in a buggy state where it causes inconsistencies when mixing settings which are mapped and ones that aren't.\r\n\r\nI propose to simply make the mapping API public, so developers have the full flexibility whether to map or not in that situation instead of mapping in functions like `setDescription`."}
