{"id":124093636,"created_at":"2015-12-28T17:18:30Z","updated_at":"2021-09-25T04:19:09Z","state":"closed","title":"Null Pointer Exception in Navigator under MacOS X","html_url":"https://github.com/gama-platform/gama/issues/1358","body":"Just for the sake of it, GAMA under MacOS X produces a lot of NPEs when navigating among the projects, especially if ones has installed El Capitan (10.11). This is a known SWT bug, referenced here: https://bugs.eclipse.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=434393, and which is supposedly fixed in Eclipse 4.5.2 (due the 26th of February, 2016).\n\nI will nevertheless produce a workaround (using Thread.setDefaultUncaughtExceptionHandler() to catch these harmless exceptions) if we dont use Mars.2 for the release.\n"}

{"id":979701150,"created_at":"2021-08-25T23:50:00Z","updated_at":"2021-08-30T14:36:43Z","state":"closed","title":"Fixed jar for issue #383","html_url":"https://github.com/mytourbook/mytourbook/pull/386","body":"No content"}
{"id":841734691,"created_at":"2021-03-26T08:55:23Z","updated_at":"2021-08-10T02:23:10Z","state":"closed","title":"BugInfoView shouldn't use NO_BACKGROUND as style for Browser (regression in Eclipse 2021-03)","html_url":"https://github.com/spotbugs/spotbugs/issues/1477","body":"The `BugInfoView` in the Eclipse plug-in sets the `SWT.NO_BACKGROUND` style on its `Browser` instance, but the documentation for the Composite class says that the use of this style bit is undefined outside `Canvas` subclasses. This use has led to a regression when using the SpotBugs Eclipse plug-in in Eclipse 2021-03. The problem is that `SWT.NO_BACKGROUND` overlaps with the new constant `SWT.EDGE` for using the experimental WebView2 browser component on Windows (see [Bug 572208](https://bugs.eclipse.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=572208) for SWT), and if that component is not available you get an exception:\r\n\r\n```\r\norg.eclipse.swt.SWTError: Not implemented [WebView2 runtime not found]\r\n\tat org.eclipse.swt.SWT.error(SWT.java:4915)\r\n\tat org.eclipse.swt.browser.Edge.createEnvironment(Edge.java:154)\r\n\tat org.eclipse.swt.browser.Edge.create(Edge.java:180)\r\n\tat org.eclipse.swt.browser.Browser.<init>(Browser.java:99)\r\n\tat de.tobject.findbugs.view.BugInfoView.createBrowser(BugInfoView.java:189)\r\n```\r\n\r\nIt seems like the fix would be simple: use `SWT.NONE` when creating the `Browser` in the `BugInfoView`."}

{"id":641318184,"created_at":"2020-06-18T15:40:46Z","updated_at":"2021-10-13T22:51:41Z","state":"closed","title":"False positives in java.lang.correctness.hardcoded-conditional","html_url":"https://github.com/returntocorp/semgrep-rules/issues/616","body":"Consider some findings from the Eclipse project:\r\n\r\n```\r\n/tmp/eclipse.platform.ui/bundles/org.eclipse.e4.ui.css.core/src/org/eclipse/e4/ui/css/core/serializers/CSSSerializer.java\r\nseverity:error rule:java.lang.correctness.hardcoded-conditional: useless if statement, always the same behavior\r\n157:\t\tif (firstSelector == false) {\r\n158:\t\t\twriter.write(\"\\n\\n\");\r\n\r\n/tmp/eclipse.platform.ui/bundles/org.eclipse.e4.ui.css.swt/src/org/eclipse/e4/ui/css/swt/helpers/URI.java\r\nseverity:error rule:java.lang.correctness.hardcoded-conditional: useless if statement, always the same behavior\r\n2858:\t\tif (!isHierarchical() ||\r\n2859:\t\t\t\t!equals(scheme, prefix.scheme(), true) ||\r\n2860:\t\t\t\t!equals(authority, prefix.authority()) ||\r\n2861:\t\t\t\t!equals(device, prefix.device()) ||\r\n2862:\t\t\t\thasAbsolutePath() != prefix.hasAbsolutePath())\r\n2863:\t\t{\r\n2864:\t\t\treturn null;\r\n\r\n/tmp/eclipse.platform.ui/bundles/org.eclipse.e4.ui.model.workbench/src/org/eclipse/e4/ui/model/fragment/impl/StringModelFragmentImpl.java\r\nseverity:error rule:java.lang.correctness.hardcoded-conditional: useless if statement, always the same behavior\r\n382:\t\t\t\tif (elements.isEmpty() == false) {\r\n383:\t\t\t\t\tret.addAll(ModelUtils.merge(targetElement, feature, elements, getPositionInList()));\r\n```\r\n\r\nUsing `if (!something) { ... }` may be preferable to `if (something == false) { ... }`, but it's still fine to write the latter version. There were a lot of these false positives on the Eclipse project, and I expect elsewhere too. Let's update this rule to get rid of these false positives."}

{"id":959550137,"created_at":"2021-08-03T21:55:55Z","updated_at":"2021-08-04T02:54:54Z","state":"closed","title":"Exception when the outline view opens when the locale is French. (Bugzilla Bug 801)","html_url":"https://github.com/JUCMNAV/projetseg-update/issues/801","body":"This issue was created automatically with bugzilla2github\n# Bugzilla Bug 801\nDate: 2012-01-23 13:32:13 -0500\nFrom: Dominique Blouin &lt;<dominique.blouin@univ-ubs.fr>&gt;\nTo:   jUCMNav &lt;<jucmnav-dev@softwareengineering.ca>&gt;\n\nLast updated: 2012-01-25 18:57:37 -0500\n\n\n## Comment 1568\nDate: 2012-01-23 13:32:13 -0500\nFrom: Dominique Blouin &lt;<dominique.blouin@univ-ubs.fr>&gt;\n\nThere is a null value send to be set as the text of a tree item of the content outline view (see trace below). After debugging, it turns out that in LabelTreeEditPart class line 178 a text value is returned. This seems to be because it is looking for an entry in the messages property file that is wrongly defined in the proeprty file. At key LabelTreeEditPart.concerns in file messages_fr.properties, the value is \"Pr\\u00e9occupation\" and it is looking for the value with an s (Pr\\u00e9occupations). Changing the value in the property file for the latter seems to fix the problem.\n\njava.lang.IllegalArgumentException: Argument cannot be null\n\tat org.eclipse.swt.SWT.error(SWT.java:4263)\n\tat {"id":930879370,"created_at":"2021-06-27T08:35:03Z","updated_at":"2021-10-08T16:21:17Z","state":"closed","title":"Use Edge Browser on Windows","html_url":"https://github.com/archimatetool/archi/issues/742","body":"The internal browser used by Eclipse (and Archi) on Windows is IE 11. That's an outdated browser and will be removed in Windows 11.\r\n\r\nWe use the internal browser for the Help System, Welcome Page, Hints window, and HTML report preview, and it can be used with jArchi.\r\n\r\nThere was an Eclipse initiative to use the Chromium browser instead. TL;DR - it's no longer happening.\r\n\r\nThere is this:\r\n\r\nhttps://bugs.eclipse.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=538991\r\n\r\nhttps://www.eclipse.org/swt/faq.php#howuseedge\r\n\r\nSo, it would require a later version of Eclipse and the end user installing stuff that I don't understand. Maybe it will work out of the box on Windows 11 and a later Eclipse version. Perhaps someone could investigate."}
